tweet: 7/ It‚Äôs true that it‚Äôs easier to change/upgrade Ethereum than Bitcoin. However, that does not mean that there is a single entity that controls the Ethereum network. Forking away the difficulty bomb is a trivial thing for miners, and they choose to upgrade nodes voluntarily.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ The 2015 Ethereum ICO being problematic is a separate issue from ETH being a security today. (As a side note, Blockstack PBC did an SEC-qualified offering for Stacks to avoid issues with initial offerings.)

Past offerings shouldn‚Äôt be confused with state of ETH today.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 6/ Let‚Äôs say Metamask shuts down, people will use other wallets. Let‚Äôs say top Ethereum miners shut down, new miners will come given incentives. Let‚Äôs say Ethereum Foundation shuts down, the code is open-source and independent devs contribute to several Ethereum implementations.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 5/ To make the case that ETH is a security, you‚Äôll need to prove (likely in a court) that ETH passes the Howey Test today. This will be nearly impossible given no single entity controls the network, decentralized mining, and how many independent entities work in the ecosystem.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 4/ New ETH tokens are produced through decentralized mining (similar to BTC token mints). These independent miners have economic incentives to operate the network. No single entity is responsible for mining or operating. Miners come and go and the network continues to function.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ In the US the Howey Test applies to determine if some asset is a security or not. A key part of the test depends on whether there is an entity or group of related entities that others rely on with an expectation of profit.

If Ethereum is a security which entity is the issuer?

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Ethereum currently uses PoW, and the mining distribution is fairly similar to Bitcoin (with a longer tail of unique miners/pools).

PoS can have more centralizing forces (e.g., rich getting richer) than PoW, but that does not mean that after the PoS switch it‚Äôll be a security.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
1/ Ethereum may not be as decentralized as Bitcoin, but on the spectrum it is on the decentralized side vs. being run by a company.

You can shut down entities like the Ethereum Foundation or ConsenSys and the Ethereum network will continue to operate and function.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
There are discussions in the Bitcoin community that ‚ÄúEthereum is a security.‚Äù This theory is flawed; I say this as a Bitcoiner who holds no ETH.

People who believe this have likely not studied the state of the Ethereum network from a Howey Test lens.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
The core idea revolves around a decentralized identifier (DID) which is a non-human readable identifier (think a really long hash). A DID is often saved at a blockchain, and this is where the Bitcoin blockchain comes in.

Only DIDs at Bitcoin layer.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@nicksdjohnson We‚Äôre talking about healing/recovering from a crash here. So at this point the miners know which transaction caused the crash. They can reboot their node.

We‚Äôre discussing making forward progress i.e, the network moves forward. For instant finality, this is a hardfork.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@nicksdjohnson Miners pick which transactions they include in the blocks they write. If forking around a failure, they‚Äôd leave the faulty transaction in the mempool to continue to make forward progress.

An instant finality chain would halt and require a (manual) hardfork.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@VitalikButerin @nicksdjohnson I think the wording of the original tweet is not ideal. PoS != instant finality. (A lot of PoS chains today do go for instant finality). @TimBeiko pointed me to the latest Etheruem docs, I was not even thinking about ETH originally üôÇ

I‚Äôm generally in the camp of allowing forks.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@nicksdjohnson Also, this is not an attack on Ethereum (which is likely your primary concern). It‚Äôs rather general commentary on the trade-off of allowing forks.

See this thread:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@nicksdjohnson They can, the faulty transaction can stay pending in the mempool as the miners forked around it.

The bigger point here is need for hardforks vs self-healing. We see hardforks in instant finality chains all the time in the industry today.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@nicksdjohnson Let‚Äôs say a transaction crashes the network nodes. Because it‚Äôs probabilistic finality, miners can fork from the previous block and heal, continue to make forward progress until a patch etc goes live.

With instant finality (typical for many PoS designs) you‚Äôd need a hardfork.

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

Also, not discussing re-org guarantee‚Äîsimply pointing out a trade-off RE self-healing ability.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: This, in the end, is really a decentralization trade-off. You trade off speed (instant finality) with the ability to fork around failures vs. relying on a few parties (often more centralized) to fix the chain, i.e., hardfork, around failures.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
Proof-of-work chains are self-healing because they allow forking. If something bad happens, miners can fork around failures without any manual input.

A flip side of instant finality is that those proof-of-stake chains don‚Äôt fork. When things go south, you need manual hardforks.

This discussion makes it clear to me that many Bitcoin community members do not understand how Stacks works and how it is similar to or different from earlier approaches like Counterparty.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: @ParchedMint Stacks data i.e, fork histories is literally secured by Bitcoin. Which is a more scalable way to secure additional data with Bitcoin than on-chain stuff.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ParchedMint Bitcoin nodes know nothing about Counterparty data and logic. You have to run special CP software to make sense of that data (similar to Stacks).

CP data verification is on Bitocoin (similar to Stacks). Counterparty data is on-chain (bad for Bitcoin), Stacks is not.

name: muneeb.btc
muneeb.btc
tweet: @ParchedMint By your definition Counterparty was also not Bitcoin NFTs. And pure Bitcoin NFTs can never exist without modifying the Bitcoin protocol (which will never happen). Bitcoin NFTs exist and are growing and your restricted definition is not going to stop them üôÇ

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
The result is a scalable way to have Bitcoin NFTs (1000x more scalable than Counterparty was, and Hyperchains will boost scalability and speed further).

Ownership and provenance on Bitcoin. Mints and sales with native BTC.

That‚Äôs how scalable Bitcoin NFTs work!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
More specifically, Stacks settles NFT ownership and transfers on Bitcoin (in small hashes). People can verify ownership by checking Bitcoin.

NFT mints and transfers can happen through pure Bitcoin transactions (but also through Stacks with lower fees).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
With Counterparty, all data and logic is written on Bitcoin main chain.

With Stacks, some data and logic goes on Bitcoin and rest on Stacks layer.

This is for scalability. On-chain approaches like Counterparty don‚Äôt scale and result in high tx fees.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
Bitcoin core protocol has no concept of NFTs, but you can define Bitcoin NFTs through additional data & logic.

Counterparty did this in 2016 and Stacks revived Bitcoin NFTs in 2021.

RSK and Liquid, however, have no coinbase rewards, so the mining incentives are solely based on network use which currently is fairly small.

Stacks has a clearer path towards catching escape velocity on mining incentives similar to modern networks like Solana, Avalanche, etc.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
$100M in mining incentives might sound like a lot but really is not. Smart contract platforms easily get into billions in mining incentives and that makes sense for security.

Coinbase rewards drive these incentives in initial years until gas fees can become more significant.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
Mining incentives for maintaining the global ledger for contracts is key.

RSK has approx $200K per month of mining incentives (I‚Äôm gathering more data). Liquid is much smaller than RSK.

Stacks had approx $100M per year of mining incentives in first year (2021).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
In the Bitocin ecosystem, projects that have global ledgers are:

- Liquid (federated model)
- RSK (merged mining)
- Stacks (open mining)

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
Smart contract platforms typically require a global ledger. You cannot implement AMMs (like Uniswap), NFT marketplaces (like OpenSea), etc., without a global ledger.

Lightning and DLCs are great, but they don't have global ledgers for contracts.

RE mining I'm not debating economic/price dynamics at all. Just how network technically works. Also, well aware of block wars :-)

name: muneeb.btc
muneeb.btc
tweet: @ercwl @Stacks @BitMEXResearch I'm making no comment about "price follows hashrate" or "hashrate follows price". I'm stating a simple fact you need hashrate to decide the winner at the technical blockchain level (the blockchain is not aware of price).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ercwl @Stacks @BitMEXResearch Please enlighten me on how a hardfork activates or sustains without mining majority support.

This is blockchains 101. Pre or post 2017 has nothing to do with it, just how these systems work.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ercwl @Stacks And we *clearly* say in Stacks docs that they are different. Please read this https://t.co/WhaYYxYQSP

Bitcoin security plays a role in Stacks security and Stacks benefits from Bitcoin security. How exactly it benefits is what we are discussing.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ercwl @Stacks Data not being on Bitcoin (and only hashes) is the right design decision because you don't want to spam the Bitcoin blockchain.

Data availability is outside Bitcoin (as it should be). History of all forks is, however, on Bitcoin (as it should be).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ercwl @Stacks You can't change the function without hardforking the network, and the hardfork will not be accepted until a miner majority adopts it.

If you want to change a few clients (without mining support) then you can go and live on that small fork and no one will care that you exist.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: @iamzensored @ercwl @Stacks No one is deny that. That is written clearly in all docs about Stacks.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@ercwl @Stacks Going back to the main point: economic majority of Stacks changing state is totally irrelevant to an attack on Stacks history (given a rule set).

That's like saying that Bitcoin user/economic majority can change Bitcoin history any day. No sane person thinks like that.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: @ercwl @Stacks Let's not get into a discussion of hardforks. Even if users want to move to a different rule set, you will still need miners to accept that mine it. If you fail to get any mining power on your new rules, that separate network will fail and die off.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: @ercwl @Stacks A user changing rules doesn't cause a hardfork on the network (only changes your local node). Mining power decides hardforks. That is precisely how blockchains work.

11/ Everything that happened within the first year of Stacks mainnet launch is hard to capture in a tweet thread.

2021 laid the foundations.
2022 is the year of growth.

Cheers to unleashing the true potential of Bitcoin: happy birthday, Stacks! üéâ

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
10/ The API by Hiro Systems, a dev tooling company in the ecosystem, saw a 6x increase recently: 50M ‚Üí 100M ‚Üí 200M ‚Üí 350M monthly requests.

We saw infrastructure and tooling improve with 120+ monthly active devs.

Stacks emerged as the fastest-growing web3 project in Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
9/ There are always new, unthinkable things. Citycoins is one such project. 

We saw the community-driven, mining-only launch for Miami and NYC. Mayor @FrancisSuarez made history by officially voting to accept the protocol treasury and by giving BTC rewards to Miami citizens.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ The .btc domains didn‚Äôt exist until recently. We saw 23,000+ registrations and an active community of .btc folks. 

Whenever you see a .btc name, you know that it‚Äôs a friendly Bitcoiner rooting for Bitcoin apps.

I love this community: ‚Çø + ”æ = üî•

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ We saw a revived interest in Bitcoin NFTs through Stacks. NFTs started on Bitcoin but got popularized by ETH. 

Now NFTs are coming back home!

140,000+ minted NFTs, 7+ marketplaces, and trading volumes going into tens of millions. This is just the beginning in many ways.

name: muneeb.btc

We saw 10x growth in deployed contracts in H2 of 2021. See the inflection point after summer: https://t.co/v3hXoVOSgi

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ Earning BTC was a completely new concept introduced by Stacks. More than $1B got locked in the contract, and people earned 1201 BTC ($51M today).

The PoX contract put Bitcoin DeFi on the map and is now the largest product in the category.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ It was unclear if the consensus and game theory would work in practice. Given the decentralized nature, there was no ‚Äúsoft launch‚Äù.

Designing blockchains is like launching rockets; you get one shot. Seeing everything work flawlessly was both exciting and a relief. It worked!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Stacks brought a new type of PoX mining and consensus to life. PoX is a cross-chain consensus between Bitcoin and Stacks and recycles PoW energy.

Connecting chains to BTC to add new features is an idea that goes back to Satoshi in 2010. Stacks turned this idea into reality!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
1/ The Stacks whitepaper came out in 2017 outlining design for Bitcoin apps.

It typically takes 2-3 years to build new blockchains. Projects that raised in the 2017 era (Filecoin, Dfinity, Stacks, etc.) went heads down and launched their mainnets in 2020-2021.

name: muneeb.btc
muneeb.btc
tweet:
10/ In summary, web3 drastically reduces the power and ownership of VCs. Venture capital still has a role, as it should in capital markets: it funds early-stage risky ideas.

Web3 is a net win for internet users. More power to the people!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
9/ In contrast to web2 companies, early community members can have an economic upside in web3 protocols (early Stacks holders are up 1,700%).

These active community members contribute ideas and improvement proposals. VCs are mostly passive while the community feels empowered.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ Stacks economics were structured in a way that no single entity even has 10% of the liquid supply. No VC, founder, or entity holds even 10%.

Even large holders have little influence on protocol changes, e.g., independent miners decide on changes (similar to Bitcoin).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ Once a crypto protocol is liquid, anyone can buy up an economic stake. This is similar to public companies. However, buying up 10% of a crypto protocol gives you far little power over the protocol than buying up 10% of a public company.

Protocols != Companies.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Web3 protocols don‚Äôt have boards. Protocol changes typically depend on mining or economic power. VCs generally are not miners.

For economic power, VCs can have too much control if the token economics are poorly designed. Most top projects design token economics carefully.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ So, what role do VCs play in web3 protocols? Can they have too much power?

VCs can help bootstrap new protocols, just like they fund early-stage startups. However, their role and power in crypto protocols is drastically reduced compared to web2 companies.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ This is in sharp contrast to web2 companies, where early users of Facebook or Twitter saw zero economic upside.

Protocols != Companies.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Web3 founders deeply understand the power of community.¬†

Almost all successful protocols had early users and enthusiasts who ended up being evangelists, not merely because they were excited about the projects but also because they had direct economic incentives.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Web3 protocols are different. These are not companies. 

These protocols can launch through mining-only (e.g., Bitcoin, CityCoins), regulated public offerings (e.g., Stacks), Reg S, and Reg CF (e.g., on platforms like CoinList and Republic).

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
9/ Bitcoiners were attracted by the Bitcoin experiment. They‚Äôve now turned into naysayers who laugh at every new experiment.¬†

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ Instead of painting VCs as evil, maximalists should spend time figuring out why Bitcoin-related projects are so underfunded and unable to produce working products, e.g., spacechains.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ Maximalists spend endless hours attacking VC money, whereas the products they use on the internet, like Twitter, Google, Zoom, etc., are all funded by VC money. Sophisticated VC investors are allocating capital to devs building next-generation apps.

Free markets at play.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ There are many shortcomings in Ethereum. However, Bitcoin currently has little to offer as alternatives. There are no major decentralized exchanges, liquidity protocols, stablecoins in the Bitcoin ecosystem.

The answer to ETH growth is to build better products for Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 5/ Maximalists have called Ethereum a ‚Äúscam‚Äù for years now. This has not stopped the growth of Ethereum. People who discover ETH or other L1s find a thriving community of builders and apps. They make up their minds based on their findings and not by an angry mob of maximalists.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

Betting against devs is not what Bitcoiners used to do.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

NFTs started on Bitcoin (using Counterparty), and now almost all of NFT economic activity is on ETH & others.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Bitcoin maximalism assumes a zero-sum world. However, we‚Äôre in an expanding crypto economy.

Attacking developers and new use-cases doesn‚Äôt help Bitcoin. It only encourages those developers and use-cases to move to other ecosystems like Ethereum and Solana.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
11/ OK, but utility tokens are different. Why is the gas token needed? 

It's needed to:

(a) pay for executing smart contracts (computations are not free).

(b) incentivize miners to operate the network (otherwise, you end up with closed/federated networks like Liquid).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
10/ The development of Liquid remains dependent on a single company. Stacks decentralized upon mainnet launch with 30+ entities in the ecosystem now; no single entity responsible for developing or operating the network.

Single point of failure vs. an open decentralized network.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

The rich people will make money on Blockstream shares. The ordinary people can benefit from the Stacks offering. (Currently, the $0.12 participants are up 1,700%.)

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 4/ This unique connection to Bitcoin enables use cases like (a) earning BTC rewards, (b) native BTC swaps, (c) lending apps where BTC stays on the Bitcoin main chain, etc. These are simply not possible on Liquid.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Stacks, however, is an open network; anyone can be a miner. There are Bitcoin-derived assets (like xBTC) on Stacks as well.

Stacks has direct connection to Bitcoin at the consensus level, contracts interact directly with Bitcoin state, and Bitcoin secures Stacks fork history.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

7/ In summary, the BTC rewards per slot depend on coinbase rewards, gas fees, and demand for the reward slots. 

Price changes in BTC/USD, STX/BTC and miner competition also impact the net reward that people see.

Current rate is ~10%‚Äîit‚Äôll be interesting to see how it evolves!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Gas fees on the network result in higher BTC rewards. This design is very different from EIP 1559: instead of burning, the gas fees result in higher BTC rewards.

A fee market is emerging on the Stacks main chain lately, so fees can play a greater role if the network grows.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ The average dollar value of a reward slot has fluctuated between $600 to $1,000 per slot. Both the STX/BTC and the BTC/USD pair changes impact this.

If both BTC and STX appreciate against USD in a week, then average rewards in USD go up and vice versa.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ The STX/BTC price pair plays a role here because most people think of rewards in terms of BTC paid out (or dollar equivalent) per month.

STX has appreciated against BTC this year: from 1,200 sats to approx 3,000 sats now.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ The first parameter is newly minted Stacks, i.e., the coinbase rewards for mining. Stacks inflation is approx 4.5% in the coming years and then drops.

If 50% of the liquid supply is locked, the rewards will be (theoretically) approx 9% per year. But there is more to it.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

What factors make the reward rate go up or down? Let‚Äôs dig in!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
1/ Stacks has a unique consensus where instead of burning electricity, miners bid in BTC. Bitcoin is used as digital energy for mining. 

The BTC is recycled and sent to Stacks holders that lock up STX in a smart contract.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ L1s can find their specialized markets and grow there.¬†

Stacks, for example, exclusively focuses on Bitcoin and to make BTC programmable and productive. Solana‚Äôs architecture might be well-suited for NYSE-type trading.

Consolidation is likely years out and may never happen.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ There is some competition between newer L1s like Solana, Algorand, Avalanche, Stacks, etc., but they‚Äôre primarily focusing on a rapidly growing market instead of trying to ‚Äúkill Ethereum.‚Äù

There are only 6-7 high-quality L1s. New ones are not entering this market.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ The ‚ÄúETH killers won‚Äôt get traction‚Äù theory is already dead. Developers are actively building, and L1s are growing.

The ‚Äúone network to rule them all‚Äù theory needs 10+ years to play out. Currently, signs point to a multi-chain world with some consolidation 5-10 years out.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ Putting aside any shortcomings of Ethereum‚Äôs design, it deserves credit for pioneering smart contracts and is the clear leader in developer adoption.

Ethereum will likely remain a big player for years. However, theories around ‚ÄúETH killers‚Äù are broken in several ways.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ If you want to start a new L1 in 2021, you‚Äôll likely find it hard to raise capital. A new smart contract L1 coming online in 2024 will likely be too late to the game.

The one exception here is privacy-focused chains, which are still new and can attract capital.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Smart contract platforms, however, remain a rapidly growing and competitive market.

The opportunity window for starting new L1 blockchains for smart contracts was in 2017-2018. These platforms typically require 2-3 years of development before mainnet launch.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

Bitcoin is the clear winner for sovereign money (with recent attempts from Ethereum to compete there.)

@TheStalwart @MrHodl @etherpropaganda @Adelgary The ETH model is conflating two things (a) gas for smart contracts with more experimental work, (b) sovereign money that is durable.

This approach cleanly separates the two with Bitcoin as durable base (sovereign money) and uses BTC security in a separate smart contract layer.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@TheStalwart @MrHodl @etherpropaganda @Adelgary I‚Äôm obviously biased here but I see this as superior for a few reasons:

1) Base layer should be simple with small attack surface i.e, Bitcoin script.

2) Scalability should come from data outside and base layer as settlements.

3) Base layer should be durable, not experimental.

tweet:
6/ In summary, NFTs emerged on Bitcoin (Counterparty and merged mining).

The next-gen NFTs on Bitcoin are more scalable as they settle on BTC (e.g., using Stacks) instead of storing all data on-chain (like Counterparty).

It‚Äôs worth knowing the original history!

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ You'll also hear that NFTs are not possible on Bitcoin. That's also false.

NFTs are currently gaining traction in ecosystems like Ethereum and Flow.

However, scalable NFTs are launching on Bitcoin. Boom wallet and the NFT drop by Cara Delevingne are examples.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ You'll often hear in the media that NFTs originated on Ethereum. That's demonstrably false.

Domain NFTs go back to 2011 (Namecoin, merged mined with Bitcoin), and popular digital art NFTs go back to 2016 (Rare Pepes, on top of Bitcoin).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Non-fungible tokens have existed on Bitcoin and separate blockchains (like BitShares) since at least 2014.

Counterparty launched on Bitcoin in 2014. Rare Pepes, the first popular digital art NFTs launched in 2016 on Counterparty (Bitcoin).

6/ Bitcoin doesn‚Äôt change, but the additional layers can.

Sovereign money should be durable and immutable (Bitcoin base layer), but you can build new features on top (additional layers like Lightning, RSK, Stacks).

Bitcoin is not a rock; it‚Äôs programmable sovereign money.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ More environment-friendly transactions are possible on Bitcoin.

The base layer maximizes decentralization and independent verification through proof-of-work. 

Additional layers like Lightning or Stacks don‚Äôt consume any PoW energy for transactions.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ Bitcoin‚Äôs base layer optimizes for decentralization and durability.

The only metric that matters for sovereign money is decentralization. The only metric that matters for a settlement layer is durability.

Bitcoin maximizes both.

Experiments happen at additional layers.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Transaction speeds are different from finality.

Lightning transactions can be fast. Microblocks on Stacks can be fast. It‚Äôs the finality on Bitcoin that takes longer, as it should.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Bitcoin is for settlements, not payments.

The additional layers, like Lightning or Stacks, is where payments happen. On Lightning, people use sats, and on Stacks, people can use stablecoins like xUSD or Bitcoin-based assets like xBTC.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
1/ People don‚Äôt think beyond the Bitcoin base layer.

L2s in Ethereum or subnets in Avalanche bring additional features to base layers.¬†

Similarly, Bitcoin layers, like Lightning for payments or RSK/Stacks for smart contracts, bring additional functionality to Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
10/ Smart contracts for Bitcoin can change the nature of the Bitcoin vs. Ethereum debate.

It's no longer about the durable store of value vs. smart contracts. You can bring smart contracts to the durable store of value (Bitcoin) instead of taking BTC to smart contract platforms.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
9/ Most people don't realize that you can directly build apps & smart contracts in the Bitcoin ecosystem: BTC as programmable money.

The competition from Ethereum can accelerate the adoption of smart contracts for Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

With all its flaws, Ethereum is the largest network by active developers and deployed smart contracts. These are facts that you can't ignore.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

Bitcoin is simple, durable, and extremely hard to change.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Ethereum as a store of value is a relatively new argument with proposed reduction in supply.

Ethereum is more experimental in nature; it evolves and changes. That property makes it a less desirable candidate for a reserve currency; you want the reserve currency to be durable.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ The lender is not trusting some other blockchain for consensus. Stacks settles transactions on Bitcoin; Bitcoin as the ultimate source of truth.

BTC movements are pure BTC transactions. The digital dollar transaction for a loan default is on Stacks that itself settles on BTC.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ The lender needs to be comfortable with the logic/code of the contract. 

This is where Clarity language's decidability plays a critical role: you can have formal proofs that the contract can only release the collateral and do nothing else.

Trust math, not people.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Party A sends a BTC transaction to Party B (the borrower), and the Clarity contract auto starts the timer on loan, expressed in BTC blocks.

If the BTC does not come back to a specified BTC address by the given BTC block, the contract will auto-release Party A's collateral.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ A Clarity contract can hold the collateral, say in a digital dollar stablecoin with 150-200% collateral. 

The Clarity contract can detect when BTC moves, so a loan can be initiated by providing loan terms (amount in BTC and time in BTC blocks) to the contract.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ Can this be implemented? Yes, let's explore.

Clarity lang, on Stacks, has direct access to Bitcoin state. This means developers can build BTC lending where BTC never leaves the main BTC chain. 

No KYC, no custodians, no middlemen.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
10/ In summary, new crypto users need to cleanly differentiate between store-of-value (Bitcoin), gas for smart contracts, and the other experiments.

Learn the basics before diving in on the deep side of the pool. The crypto rabbit hole is exciting but here be dragons.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
9/ The two required readings for new crypto users should be:

(a) "The case for a small allocation to Bitcoin" by Wences Casares, and 
(b) "The economics and valuation of utility protocols" by John Pfeffer.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ The biggest mistake new users make is to confuse the rise of Bitcoin with experimental new assets. Bitcoin is the rise of a digital store-of-value.

The new experimental assets are not a store-of-value.
Gas for smart contracts is also not a store-of-value.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ The "other" category has subcategories like storage networks, governance tokens (for liquidity protocols, exchanges), etc. The rate of innovation is so rapid that even full-time research analysts can't keep up.

(I'll expand this separately but collapsing here for simplicity.)

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: 6/ Use cases outside of the two biggest ones (SoV and gas) are even more experimental. Several interesting new assets belong in this "other" category. There is potential, but for a new crypto user, the important thing to remember is that it's the riskiest category.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ Store-of-value should not be confused with gas for smart contracts. That is an entirely different market.

SoV is not a competitive market, with a clear winner (Bitcoin).
Gas for smart contracts is a competitive market, and it's becoming more competitive.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ Bitcoin as a store-of-value is a use case with product-market fit. That's why corporate treasuries are building Bitcoin positions.

What crypto asset is a hedge against inflation or a collapse of bond markets? Answer: Bitcoin and, more importantly, only Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Bitcoin smart contracts, like it or not, are already here. 

In fact, they‚Äôre more powerful because (a) Bitcoin has established itself as a trillion dollar hard money, (b) they benefit from the secure base layer, and (c) the settlement design is scalable.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ There is nothing fundamental about Bitcoin that stops smart contracts. 

Bitcoin designers, very carefully, built it so that the base layer has a small attack vector (i.e, limited script).

This leaves several options open to implementing smart contracts.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

You can be expressive with *decidable* languages. Being Turing complete i.e, not decidable is a security problem.

7/ Open membership and globally shared state are critical aspects of modern decentralized systems.

Diem (formerly Libra) is not a decentralized system because it doesn‚Äôt have open membership. PGP won‚Äôt give you decentralized domains because it doesn‚Äôt have globally shared state.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Final definition:

‚ÄúA decentralized system is a type of open distributed system that manages globally shared state without any single entity having majority administrative control.‚Äù

This gives us a complete, specific definition.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ Iteration 2: ‚ÄúA decentralized system is a type of distributed system that manages globally shared state without any single entity having majority administrative control.‚Äù

Better but something is still missing. You can get these properties in a closed member group as well.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ Globally shared state is the set of information that distrusting nodes on the network (a) need to agree on and (b) can modify independently.

Let‚Äôs add that to our initial definition.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ The above definition is not complete. 

There are other types of distributed systems that lack central points of control e.g., peer-to-peer systems.

What‚Äôs the difference between decentralized systems and traditional peer-to-peer systems then?

Answer: globally shared state.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Every distributed system is not decentralized. An initial definition:

Iteration 1: ‚ÄúA decentralized system is a type of distributed system where no single entity has majority administrative control.‚Äù

Now let‚Äôs improve it to make it precise.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ We talk a lot about decentralized systems in the crypto industry.

What defines a decentralized system? Some people try to contrast it with a distributed system. I find that confusing.

I view decentralized systems as a subset of the broader term distributed systems.

name: muneeb.btc

3/ All data from Stacks chain automatically settles on Bitcoin every block (an analogy would be a lightning channel that auto settles every block).

Stacks holders participate in consensus by locking STX in a smart contract to earn BTC (the BTC from miner bids).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Miners compete in leader election on the Bitcoin chain and bid in BTC. A Verifiable Random Function (VRF) selects the winner.

Winning miner writes the Stacks block, collects newly minted STX, and collects the gas fees for smart contracts.

Mining is open to anyone.

name: muneeb.btc

Sharing compute power and network security with Bitcoin is critical for the long-term durability of smart contracts.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet: @gakonst @PanosJee Because the design of the language can have limitations. See Clarity lang for example. You make the tradeoff of limiting the language (can still write generic programs) and being able to know *precisely* what the program will do upon execution.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
Also, we can give Solidity the credit for all the early innovation and still work on better designs. No need to bash anything or anyone. Improvements happen by finding structural flaws, admitting them, and correcting them.

That‚Äôs how we mature as an industry.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
This is a common misunderstanding so worth addressing.

Yes, vulnerabilities exist in any code. The night and day difference is being able to know what the code is going to do *before* you execute the code.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@gakonst @PanosJee That's not true at all. 

Complexity does not go through the roof (if anything reduces).

Developers don't need to do anything, they just write code. Highly encourage you to look more into decidable langs.

Solidity enabled a lot of innovation, not taking anything away from it.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
@gakonst @PanosJee That‚Äôs what formal verification is for correct? To catch those bugs before they go to production.

There are two options here, either (a) you can know what the smart contract is going to do before it executes, or (b) you cannot. Option (a) is strictly superior to (b).

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

Formal verification should be required; just manual audits are not enough.

It leads to a model of BTC as center of gravity, the reserve currency.

Other assets settle on the BTC chain and derive their security from it.

Everything eventually gets packaged up as a hash on BTC chain.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:

name: muneeb.btc

tweet:

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
8/ Web 3 emerging on top of Bitcoin is more than just a theory for me.

I believe in this outcome enough that the technical architecture of Stacks 2.0 and Clarity lang follows this model.

It‚Äôs exciting to see many different experiments and designs!

<finish>

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
7/ The ‚Äúgood enough‚Äù protocol that reaches market domination wins.

There can be only one narrow waist.

It doesn‚Äôt need to be perfect, but it absolutely needs to be universal.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
6/ The narrow waist cannot be complex but radically simple.

Bitcoin fits that property. Other more complex blockchains don‚Äôt.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
5/ A key property of internet‚Äôs narrow waist (IP protocol) is that its universal.

For a new protocol to become the ‚Äúnarrow waist‚Äù of crypto it‚Äôd need to become more universal than Bitcoin.

That‚Äôs theoretically possible but unlikely to happen.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
4/ New protocols can anchor to security of Bitcoin and extend Bitcoin.

This is an under-explored design space but is beginning to change.

Clarity for example offers smart contracts that anchor to security of Bitcoin without modifying Bitcoin.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
3/ Bitcoin has network effects.

If something can be done on top of Bitcoin, it will eventually get done on top of Bitcoin vs a smaller ecosystem.

name: muneeb.btc
tweet:
2/ Bitcoin is not merely a payment application of consensus protocols.

It‚Äôs the largest, most stable consensus protocol that is minimal by design.

IP is minimal by design; it does one job and does it well. Same for Bitcoin.
